{{refimprove|date=March 2012}} [[File:Logo Sign.svg|thumb|300px|alt=A blue sign consisting of the words "Food-Exit 44" and the logos of the following fast food restaurants: Blimpie, IHOP, KFC, McDonald's, and Subway|An example of a typical American logo sign]] '''Logo signs''' (also known as '''specific service signs''' or '''Logo service signs''', or colloquially as '''Big Blue Signs''') are [[blue]] [[Traffic sign|road signs]] used on freeways that display the logos of businesses prior to an [[interchange (road)|interchange]]. Typically, a business pays fees to a transportation department (or to a subcontractor of a transportation department such as [[Lamar Advertising]] subsidiary Interstate Logos) to have their [[logo]]s displayed on a large panel alongside other [[business]]es.
==History== ===In the United States=== In the [[United States]], logo signs were permitted on rural [[Interstate Highway System|Interstate]]s in 1965 as part of the [[Highway Beautification Act]]. Originally, such signs were limited to the following categories: gas, food, lodging, and camping. The 1976 amendments to the Highway Beautification Act expanded the program to federal-aid primary rural highways. In 2000, provisions for allowing logo signs on urban highways (as long as adequate sign spacing can be maintained) were added to the [[Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices]]; however, as of 2018 not all states have adopted these provisions, with some states (such as [[California Department of Transportation|California]] and [[New York State Department of Transportation|New York]]) continuing to restrict the installation of logo signs to rural highways only. As of 2018, logo signs are permitted on urban highways in 18 states ([[Arizona Department of Transportation|Arizona]], [[Colorado Department of Transportation|Colorado]], [[Florida Department of Transportation|Florida]], [[Georgia Department of Transportation|Georgia]], [[Iowa Department of Transportation|Iowa]], [[Louisiana Department of Transportation|Louisiana]], [[Massachusetts Department of Transportation|Massachusetts]], [[Minnesota Department of Transportation|Minnesota]], [[Nevada Department of Transportation|Nevada]], [[New Jersey Department of Transportation|New Jersey]], [[North Carolina Department of Transportation|North Carolina]], [[Oregon Department of Transportation|Oregon]], [[Tennessee Department of Transportation|Tennessee]], [[Texas Department of Transportation|Texas]], [[Utah Department of Transportation|Utah]], [[Virginia Department of Transportation|Virginia]], [[Washington State Department of Transportation|Washington]], and [[Wisconsin Department of Transportation|Wisconsin]]), with Tennessee being the most recent state (as of 2015) to repeal the restriction for installing logo signs on rural highways only. The 2000 MUTCD also added the attractions category, followed by the 2003 MUTCD which added the 24-hour pharmacies category.<ref name=MUTCD2003>{{cite book |author= Staff |year= 2004 |origyear=2003 |chapter= Chapter 2F: Specific Service Signs |title= [[Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices]] |chapter-url= https://ceprofs.civil.tamu.edu/ghawkins/MUTCD%202003-Revision%201.pdf |format= PDF |edition= Revision&nbsp;1, 2003 |location= Washington, DC |publisher= [[Federal Highway Administration]] |pages= 2F-1–2F-6 |isbn= 9780935403817}}</ref> Logo signs in the United States are limited to six logos per sign, and additional signs may be used up to a total of four in each direction per interchange.<ref name=MUTCD2009>{{cite book |author= Staff |year= 2009 |chapter= Chapter 2J: Specific Service Signs |chapter-url= http://mutcd.fhwa.dot.gov/pdfs/2009/part2ithu2n.pdf |format=PDF |title= Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices |edition= 2009 |location= Washington, DC |publisher= Federal Highway Administration |pages= 312–19 |isbn= 9781615835171}}</ref> In 2006, the [[Federal Highway Administration]] issued an interim approval to allow more than six logo panels per service type on up to two signs per direction,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mutcd.fhwa.dot.gov/res-interim_approvals.htm | title=Interim Approvals Issued by FHWA | work=Federal Highway Administration | accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref> which was eventually incorporated into the 2009 Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices.
In California, as well as on the [[Pennsylvania Turnpike]] the label "GAS" is replaced by "FUEL".
===In Canada===
Logo signs are found along major highways in [[Ontario]], namely 400-series highways 400 and 401. A separate signage is used for [[ONroute]] rest areas.
