{{unreferenced|date=August 2017}}
This article provides a collection of the '''[[etymologies]]''' of the [[name]]s of the [[regions of Peru]].
{| class="wikitable" ! State name !! Language of origin !! Source word !! Meaning and Notes |- | [[Amazonas Region|Amazonas]] || [[Spanish language|Spanish]] || ''Amazonas'' || Named after the [[Amazon River]]. This name was given by [[Francisco de Orellana]] originally to [[Marañón River]], after dealing with a local ethnic group in which men and women alike were defending themselves. The name given is merely historical, because the river does not cross the territory of this region. |- | [[Ancash Region|Ancash]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] || ''anqash'' || "Blue". The name comes from the Ancash Quechuan word "anqash" which means 'blue'. It was the name of a stream tributary of the [[Santa River]] (Ancachs River) on whose banks was fought the [[Battle of Yungay]] on 28 February 1839. The name of this region, formerly the Huaylas Department was changed by the temporary President [[Agustín Gamarra]] by Supreme Decree in commemoration of the victory in these battle. In 1940 "Ancachs" was finally changed to "Ancash". |- | [[Apurímac Region|Apurímac]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]]|| ''apu rimaq'' || Named after the [[Apurímac River]]. ''Apu rimaq'' in Quechua means 'one who speaks with the gods' or 'oracle greater'. It is a region run by mountain ranges. |- | [[Arequipa Region|Arequipa]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] || ''Ari, qhipay'' || The region takes its name from its capital city, [[Arequipa]]. The city's name comes from the Quechua phrase "Ari, qhipay" which means "yes, stay" which is said to have been the response of the fourth Sapa Inca &mdash; [[Mayta Cápac]] &mdash; upon seeing the site of the great city, which was later destroyed in an earthquake but reestablished by the Spanish in 1540. |- | [[Ayacucho Region|Ayacucho]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] || ''aya k'uchu'' || "Corner of the dead". The [[Wari culture]] developed in [[Huanta Province]], until they were assimilated by the expansion of the [[Incas]]. [[Viracocha]] conquered the region, finding a stubborn opposition by Pocras who were slain in a corner of Parcos, so after it was called toponymic ''Ayawarkuna'', which means "place where dead hang". Such was the carnage that caused the fighting between the [[Incas]] and the natives that these events resulted in the Quechua name ''Ayak'uchu'', which literally means "corner of the Dead". On 15 February 1825, by Order of the Liberator [[Simón Bolívar]], original names ([[Ayacucho|Huamanga]] and [[Ayacucho Region|Department of Huamanga]]) were replaced by the name of Ayacucho, in recognition of the victors of the [[Battle of Ayacucho]]." |- | [[Cajamarca Region|Cajamarca]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] || ''kasha marka'' || The region takes its name from its capital city, [[Cajamarca]]. The city name was registered by the early chroniclers as ''Caxamarca'', in Quechua, ''kasha marka'' or "town (marka) of thorns (kasha)" in reference to the abundance of the San Pedro cacti (''[[Echinopsis pachanoi]]'') in the valley where it is located the city. |- | [[Callao Region|Callao]] || [[Spanish language|Spanish]] || ''callao'' || In Spanish, ''callao'' means pebble or river cobble, which means the same as the French word "caillou" and the Portuguese word "calhao". One of the qualities of Callao are its clean and rocky beaches. |- | [[Cusco Region|Cusco]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] via [[Aymara language|Aymara]] || ''qusqu wanka'' || "Rock of the owl".{{dubious|reason=It is quite well established that the Quechua word ''qosqo'', meaning ''navel'', is the origin of the name|date=August 2017}} The region takes its name from its capital city, [[Cusco]]. It is believed that the Quechua name 'Qusqu' with which it was found at the time of the [[Spanish conquest of the Inca Empire|conquest of the Inca Empire]], has Aymara origin, and derives from the phrase ''qusqu wanka'' ("rock of the owl") from the [[Inca_mythology#Inca_foundation_legends|legend of Ayar Brothers]], where Ayar Auca flying with his own wings, occupies the site where it was Cusco, then settles on a rock in the area and he turns to stone, becoming a symbol of the occupation. |- | [[Huancavelica Region|Huancavelica]] || [[Quechua languages|Quechua]] || ''wanka willka'' || The region takes its name from its capital city, [[Huancavelica]]. In the [[Ancient Peruvian cultures|pre-Incan era]], Huancavelica was known as the ''wanka willka'' region or "the place where the grandsons of the [[Wankas]] live". |- |}
==References== {{reflist}}
