[[File:Cl-triconti-en.PNG|thumb|280px|Map of '''Tricontinental Chile''' with possessions in South America, [[Oceania]] ([[Easter Island]]), and [[Antarctica]] ([[Chilean Antarctic Territory]])]]
'''Tricontinental Chile''' ({{lang-es|Chile tricontinental}}) is a [[geopolitic]]al concept denoting [[Chile]]'s unique position with its mainland in [[South America]], [[Easter Island]] in [[Oceania]] and the [[Chilean Antarctic Territory]] in [[Antarctica]].<ref>{{ cite web|title= Chile: un país tricontinental |url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http://www.icarito.cl/medio/articulo/0,0,38035857_152308993_152512596_1,00.html&title=Chile%3A%20un%20pa%C3%ADs%20tricontinental |accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>

==Continental Chile==
{{Main|Continental Chile}}
Continental Chile corresponds to the strip of territory along the southwestern coast of [[South America]] and its adjacent islands. Almost the entire population lives in continental Chile, which extends from 17°30’ S, at the border with [[Peru]] and [[Bolivia]], to the [[Diego Ramírez Islands]] at  56°30’ S. The maximum width of {{convert|445|km|abbr=on}} is at 52°21’ S, at the [[Strait of Magellan]], whilst the minimum width is at 31°37’ S between Punta Amolanas and Paso de la Casa de Piedra.

==Insular Chile==
{{Main|Insular Chile}}
Insular Chile consists of a group of islands of volcanic origin in the [[Oceania|South Pacific]], far from the continental coast. In the eastern group are the [[Juan Fernández Islands]] and the [[Desventuradas Islands]], which are grouped with South America, while [[Easter Island]] and the [[Isla Salas y Gómez]] geographically belong to [[Polynesia]] in [[Oceania]]. Easter Island (or Rapa Nui), is the westernmost part of Chile, situated at 27°S and 109°W.

==Chilean Antarctica==
{{Main|Chilean Antarctic Territory}}
The [[Chilean Antarctic Territory]] is a claim of {{convert|1250000|km2|abbr=on}} of Antarctica between 53°W and 90°W and from 60°S to the [[South Pole]], overlapping with the claims of [[Argentina]] and the [[United Kingdom]]. As a signatory to the [[Antarctic Treaty System]], Chile has accepted the suspension of its claims of sovereignty without renouncing them, as well as the establishment of a conservation zone for scientific development.

If the Antarctic claim was included, the total area of Chile would be {{convert|2006096|km2|abbr=on}}, while the distance between the northern and southern extremes would be more than {{convert|8000|km|abbr=on}}.

Between these three distinct zones is the so-called [[Chilean Sea]]; portions of the [[continental shelf]] lie within the [[exclusive economic zone]] of {{convert|370|km|abbr=on}}.

